84","1290":"1290","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","of Wich Malbank,Cheshire,England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of Nantwich, Cheshire, England":"Nantwich, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maisterson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>maister</i> ‘master’ + <i>-son</i>. Compare   Master  .","Irish: in Ireland, this is usually the English name in 1 above. However, it was also adopted for Irish <i>Mac an Mháighistir</i> ‘son of the master’, also Anglicized as   McMaster  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Master","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Amar, Dhimant, Pravin, Amit, Aruna, Bhanu, Gaurang, Gopal, Haren, Jagu, Jayesh, Kalpesh.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>maister</i> ‘master’ (Old French <i>maistre</i>). The word had a wide range of applications, and the reference in surnames may be to a schoolmaster, to the master of a farm or house, to the master of an apprentice, or to a ship's captain. In Scotland the eldest sons of barons and the uncles of lords were called <i>Masters</i>, but this is not primarily a Scottish surname.","German: dialect form of   Meister   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"McMaster","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac an Mháighistir</i> ‘son of the master’, meaning ‘teacher’ or ‘cleric’. It could also be applied in the sense of ‘lord’ or ‘owner’. This name was sometimes Anglicized as   Masterson  ."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":28,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Cecilia Maisterson Mrs was born about 1262, in Cheshire, England. She married Robert Maisterson of Wich Malbank about 1283, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1312, at the age of 51."},"et":{"Abt 1262–1312":"umbes 1262–1312","1260–1298":"1260–1298","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1262–1312":"1262–1312","Abt 1262":"umbes 1262","Abt 1283":"umbes 1283","1312":"1312","Aft 1298":"pärast 1298","1298":"1298","1262":"1262","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","about 1284":"umbes 1284","1290":"1290","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","of Wich Malbank,Cheshire,England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Nantwich, Cheshire, England":"Nantwich, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1262–1312":"noin 1262–1312","1260–1298":"1260–1298","1284–Male":"1284–Kuollut","1262–1312":"1262–1312","Abt 1262":"noin 1262","Abt 1283":"noin 1283","1312":"1312","Aft 1298":"1298 jälkeen","1298":"1298","1262":"1262","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","about 1284":"noin 1284","1290":"1290","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engl